body:
### Describe the bug

It seems that with 2.7.1.Final it is no longer possible to decorate the built-in bean `Event<T>`. This was still possible in October, with version 2.2.3.Final.

### Expected behavior

The built-in bean `Event<T>` should be decorate-able as per the [CDI Spec](https://jakarta.ee/specifications/cdi/2.0/cdi-spec-2.0.html#decorators)

> Decorators may be associated with any managed bean that is not itself an interceptor or decorator, or with any built-in bean other than the built-in bean with type `BeanManager` and qualifier `@Default`.


### Actual behavior

The decorator is picked up by Quarkus, because if I remove the `@Priority`, then the log-message
`INFO: The decorator com.example.EventDecorator does not declare any @Priority. It will be assigned a default priority value of 0.`
appears. But it is not applied to the bean, because the test fails.

### How to Reproduce?

Define two classes like so:
```
@Decorator
@Priority(Interceptor.Priority.APPLICATION)
public abstract class EventDecorator<T> implements Event<T>, Serializable {

    @Inject
    @Delegate
    @Any
    Event<T> delegate;

    @Inject
    EventCollector eventCollector;

    @Override
    public void fire(final T event) {
        eventCollector.collect(event);
        delegate.fire(event);
    }
}
```
and
```

@ApplicationScoped
public class EventCollector {

    List<Object> firedEvents = new ArrayList<>();

    public List<Object> getFiredEvents() {
        return firedEvents;
    }

    public <T> void collect(final T event) {
        firedEvents.add(event);
    }
}
```
And run the following Test:
```

@QuarkusTest
class EventDecoratorTest {

    @Inject
    EventCollector eventCollector;

    @Inject
    Event<Integer> event;

    @Test
    void testDecorator(){
        event.fire(42);

        assertThat(eventCollector.getFiredEvents()).contains(42);
    }
}
```

